==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Fife
<hw>Fife</hw> <pr>(f⟦imac⟧f)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>fifre</ets>, OHG. <ets>pf⟦imac⟧fa</ets>, LL. <ets>pipa</ets> pipe,
<ets>pipare</ets> to play on the pipe, fr. L. <ets>pipire</ets>,
<ets>pipare</ets>, to peep, pip, chirp, as a chiken. See
<er>Pipe</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>A small shrill pipe,
resembling the piccolo flute, used chiefly to accompany the drum in
military music.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Fife major</b></col> <fld>(Mil.)</fld>, <cd>a
noncommissioned officer who superintends the fifers of a regiment.</cd>
-- <col><b>Fife rail</b></col>. <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>A
rail about the mast, at the deck, to hold belaying pins, etc.</cd>
<sd>(b)</sd> <cd>A railing around the break of a poop
deck.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fife</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Fife
<hw>Fife</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Fifed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>fifing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To play on a fife.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fifer</ent>⟦br⟧
